        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "QoI relevance acceptance criteria",
        "description": "Primary QoI (peak wear-particle concentration and spatial distribution) must be directly linked to the clinical endpoint (osteolysis risk) via documented mechanistic rationale; secondary QoIs (shear stress, fluid velocity) must be traceable to the primary QoI."
      },
      "rationale": "Peak wear-particle concentration is the primary driver of macrophage-mediated osteolysis in TKR, as established by Purdue et al. (2007) and Ingham & Fisher (2005). The mechanistic pathway from particle concentration to osteolysis is documented in the model rationale document (MRD-TKR-001). Secondary QoIs (wall shear stress, interstitial fluid velocity) are linked to particle transport via Stokes drag formulation."
    },
    {
